#compdef qw
# ============================================================================
# qw - quicwire: encrypted mesh-networking agent using
#       QUIC CONNECT-IP tunnels (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Nexodus contributors (nexodus-io)
# Upstream: https://github.com/nexodus-io/quicwire
#
# `qw` (quicwire) is a mesh-networking agent that
# establishes encrypted point-to-point tunnels between
# peer endpoints using the IETF MASQUE CONNECT-IP
# protocol (RFC 9484, building on RFC 9000 QUIC + RFC
# 9221 unreliable datagrams). It runs as a single
# binary that can simultaneously act as both client
# and server (or either, with `--disable-client` /
# `--disable-server`), making it easy to build mesh
# topologies where each node maintains tunnels to
# multiple peers.
#
# The pitch over WireGuard: QUIC's connection-migration
# semantics + 0-RTT handshakes + multiplexed streams
# mean quicwire tunnels survive client-side IP changes
# (mobile-to-mobile network swaps, NAT rebinding) without
# the WireGuard-style "tunnel drops, must reconfigure"
# behaviour. Tradeoff: extra latency from user-space
# QUIC stack vs. WireGuard's in-kernel implementation.
#
# Usage:
#   qw --config-file <config.yaml> [options]
#
# Flags (urfave/cli/v2):
#
# Tunnel Options:
#   --config-file <file>    - quicwire network config file
#                              (YAML; required)
#   --disable-client        - run as server-only (don't
#                              dial outbound tunnels)
#   --disable-server        - run as client-only (don't
#                              accept inbound tunnels)
#
# Misc Options:
#   --cpuprofile <file>     - write Go CPU pprof data to
#                              <file>
#   --memprofile <file>     - write Go memory pprof data
#                              to <file>
#
# Global flags:
#   -h, --help              - print help
#   -v, --version           - print version
#
# Environment:
#   QUICWIRE_LOGLEVEL       - any non-empty value
#                              enables debug-level
#                              development logging (zap)
#
# The quic-go lane is built on `github.com/quic-go/quic-
# go v0.34.0` (declared verbatim at upstream go.mod HEAD
# as a direct dep, imported throughout internal/), the
# canonical Go QUIC library by Marten Seemann -
# github.com/quic-go/quic-go, 11000+ stars. Seemann was
# formerly on the Chrome QUIC team at Google, where IETF
# QUIC was originally developed before being de-Google-
# ified and handed to the IETF working group. He started
# the Go implementation in 2016 (back when QUIC was
# still "Google QUIC", before IETF QUIC stabilized as
# RFC 9000 in May 2021), and his Go implementation
# co-evolved with Chrome's C++ implementation through
# the full IETF interop test cycle.
#
# quic-go implements RFC 9000 (QUIC v1) + RFC 9001 (QUIC
# TLS) + RFC 9002 (loss recovery + congestion control)
# + RFC 9221 (unreliable datagrams) + RFC 9298 (CONNECT-
# UDP for MASQUE) + RFC 9484 (CONNECT-IP for MASQUE) +
# the experimental QUIC-V2 (RFC 9369) + qlog telemetry.
# Congestion control via NewReno (default) or Cubic
# (experimental). Crypto delegated to the Go standard
# library's `crypto/tls` package, which gained QUIC
# support in Go 1.21 (Aug 2023).
#
# The library has been adopted by:
#   - Caddy server (HTTP/3 default since Caddy 2.6)
#   - libp2p (transport-quic implementation)
#   - algorand-go (validator protocol)
#   - syncthing (alternative to TCP transport)
#   - cloudflared (Cloudflare Tunnel client)
#   - nexodus-io/quicwire (THIS BINARY)
#   - quic-go/masque-go (HTTP/3 CONNECT-UDP proxy)
#
# quicwire uses quic-go's CONNECT-IP MASQUE extension
# (via the `cmd` package's `quicwire.NewQuicWire()`)
# to tunnel arbitrary IP packets through QUIC streams -
# the result is a layer-3 mesh VPN where each tunnel
# session migrates cleanly across peer IP changes.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 249 :: QUIC / RFC 9000 (UDP-based transport with
#              TLS 1.3 integrated + multiplexed streams)
# Round 1446 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 249
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : quinn-rs/quinn              [R1445 _quicssh-rs]
#   Go      : quic-go/quic-go             [R1446 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : nodejs-undici               [R1447 closing]
#             (with HTTP/3 backend)
#
# quic-go is structurally interesting in this axis
# because of its *single-author canonical-but-google-
# adjacent* governance shape. Marten Seemann started
# quic-go in 2016 while QUIC was still Google's
# experimental transport and there was no IETF spec to
# track against - the early Go implementation literally
# co-evolved with Chrome's reference C++ implementation
# via cross-impl interop testing on Google's test rig.
#
# When Seemann left Google in 2017 to work on libp2p
# (now ProtocolLabs), the library moved out of his
# personal GitHub namespace into the dedicated `quic-
# go` GitHub org, but stayed under his maintainership
# rotation. The library reached canonical-Go-QUIC
# status before any spec-author-adjacent alternative
# emerged - Seemann's prior Chrome QUIC team
# experience meant the implementation tracked the
# IETF spec drafts ahead of the Go ecosystem at large.
#
# Structural commentary on the cross-language canonicals:
#   - quinn-rs/quinn (Rust): clean split between sans-I/O
#     `quinn-proto` state machine + tokio-async `quinn`
#     wrapper; rustls or openssl crypto; BBR / NewReno /
#     Cubic congestion
#   - quic-go/quic-go (Go): single-author canonical by
#     Marten Seemann (former Chrome QUIC team); crypto
#     via stdlib crypto/tls (with QUIC support since
#     Go 1.21); NewReno default + experimental Cubic
#   - nodejs-undici (Node): Matteo Collina's fast HTTP
#     client; HTTP/3 (QUIC) support since v6.0 (2024);
#     promoted into Node stdlib `fetch()` starting
#     Node 18 (Oct 2022)
#
# Cross-language interop validated by the IETF QUIC
# working group's interop test matrix, which ran weekly
# during the 2017-2021 spec development cycle and
# continues as a maintenance test suite. quinn + quic-go
# + msquic + ngtcp2 + quiche + lsquic all talk to each
# other across all RFC 9000 features; the qlog telemetry
# format (RFC 9369 draft) provides a cross-impl debug
# log format.
# ============================================================================

_qw() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--config-file[quicwire network configuration file]:file:_files -g "*.{yaml,yml}"' \
        '--disable-client[disable client (dialing tunnels) function]' \
        '--disable-server[disable server (accepting tunnels) function]' \
        '--cpuprofile[write Go CPU pprof data]:file:_files' \
        '--memprofile[write Go memory pprof data]:file:_files' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[print version]'
}

_qw "$@"
